class StockSpanner {
public:
    stack<int> s;
    StockSpanner() {

    }

    int next(int price) {
        int count = 1;
        while (!s.empty() && s.top() <= price) {
            count += s.top();
            s.pop();
        }
        s.push(count);
        return count;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses a stack to keep track of the count of consecutive days for which the stock price was less than or equal to the current day's price. It iteratively pops elements from the stack and adds them to the count until it finds an element greater than the current day's price, then pushes the count onto the stack. This approach ensures that the count is calculated efficiently in O(n) time complexity, where n is the number of days. The space complexity is also O(n) due to the use of a stack to store the counts.

